{"refrec": {"BRefID": 294744, "RR": "<b>Nakov, T.; Beaulieu, J.M.; Alverson, A.J.</b> (2018). Accelerated diversification is related to life history and locomotion in a hyperdiverse lineage of microbial eukaryotes (Diatoms, Bacillariophyta). <i>New Phytol. 219(1)</i>: 462-473. <a href=\"https://hdl.handle.net/10.1111/nph.15137\" target=\"_blank\">https://hdl.handle.net/10.1111/nph.15137</a>", "BEntID": 286814, "PublicFlag": 1, "CheckedFlag": 0, "wosflag": 1, "vabbflag": 1, "RefStringPartII": ". <i>New Phytol. 219(1)</i>: 462-473. <a href=\"https://hdl.handle.net/10.1111/nph.15137\" target=\"_blank\">https://hdl.handle.net/10.1111/nph.15137</a>", "DocTypID": 8, "MarineFlag": 1, "FreshFlag": 0, "BrackishFlag": 0, "TerrestrialFlag": 0, "Authorstring": "Nakov, T.; Beaulieu, J.M.; Alverson, A.J.", "OrigTitleTranslFlag": 0, "Authorstringtrunc": "Nakov, T. <i>et al.</i>", "Englishabstract": "Patterns of species richness are commonly linked to life history strategies. In diatoms, an exceptionally diverse lineage of photosynthetic heterokonts important for global photosynthesis and burial of atmospheric carbon, lineages with different locomotory and reproductive traits differ dramatically in species richness, but any potential association between life history strategy and diversification has not been tested in a phylogenetic framework.  We constructed a time\u2010calibrated, 11\u2010gene, 1151\u2010taxon phylogeny of diatoms \u2013 the most inclusive diatom species tree to date. We used this phylogeny, together with a comprehensive inventory of first\u2013last occurrences of Cenozoic fossil diatoms, to estimate ranges of expected species richness, diversification and its variation through time and across lineages.  Diversification rates varied with life history traits. Although anisogamous lineages diversified faster than oogamous ones, this increase was restricted to a nested clade with active motility in the vegetative cells.  We propose that the evolution of motility in vegetative cells, following an earlier transition from oogamy to anisogamy, facilitated outcrossing and improved utilization of habitat complexity, ultimately leading to enhanced opportunity for adaptive divergence across a variety of novel habitats. Together, these contributed to a species radiation that gave rise to the majority of present\u2010day diatom diversity.", "AbstractOtherLang": null, "BibLvlCode": "AS", "StandardTitle": "Accelerated diversification is related to life history and locomotion in a hyperdiverse lineage of microbial eukaryotes (Diatoms, Bacillariophyta)", "OrigTitleLangCode": "en", "UserAccessRight": null, "UserAccID": null, "AuthorKeywords": "anisogamy; diatoms; diversification; life history; motility; oogamy", "OtherDescriptors": null, "Notes": null, "AnaPub": 2018, "MonPub": null, "DateUpdate": "2018-07-12                    ", "DateCreate": "2018-04-18                    ", "SecASFANote": null, "ProID": null, "ConfID": null, "PeerRev": 1, "VlizCoreFlag": 1, "WoScode": "WOS:000434153200043", "VABBcode": null, "OpenAcc": 1, "Handle": "10.1111/nph.15137"}, "refs": null, "anarec": {"AnaID": 294744, "PubliDate": 2018, "Pagination": "462-473", "XtraPublOfAnaID": null, "ISBN": null, "Volume": "219", "Issue": "1", "BRefMon": null, "BRefMonRR": null, "BRefXtra": null, "BRefXtraRR": null, "SerBRefID": 43570, "SerRR": "New Phytologist. Wiley-Blackwell: Oxford.  ISSN 0028-646X; e-ISSN 1469-8137", "StandardTitleSer": "New Phytologist", "ISSN": "0028-646X", "AbbrevSer": "New Phytol.", "StandardTitleMon": null, "StartPage": 462, "Pages": 12, "ToPubliDate": null, "BRefBibLvlCode": "S", "SerNotes": null}, "monrec": null, "serrec": null, "relations": null, "relationsRev": null, "addrec": null, "othpubs": null, "ownerships": null, "authors": [{"AutName": "Nakov", "Firstname": "Teofil", "Initials": "T.", "Affiliation": null, "Discriminator": null, "CorporateFlag": 0, "BEntID": 286814, "AutID": 322421, "OrderNr": 1, "DegrID": null, "EditorFlag": 0, "CorrespFl